---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import StatusBadge from '../../components/StatusBadge.astro';
import { snapshot, industries, entitiesInCohort, SNAP_DATE } from '../../lib/data';
import { itemListDataset, breadcrumb } from '../../lib/jsonld';
const inds = [...industries().values()];
const allCohorts = inds.flatMap((ind) => [...ind.subniches.values()].map((sn) => ({ ind, sn })));
const desc = `Evidaxis coverage atlas: ${snapshot.counts.entities} AI systems across ${allCohorts.length} cohorts, plus an explicit map of what is not yet measured.`;
const listJson = itemListDataset({ path: '/coverage/', name: 'Evidaxis coverage atlas', description: desc, snap: snapshot, entities: snapshot.entities });
---
<Base title="Coverage atlas | Evidaxis" description={desc} canonical="/coverage/" jsonLd={[listJson, breadcrumb([{ name: 'Coverage', path: '/coverage/' }])]}>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Coverage atlas · Epoch 01</p>
      <h1>{snapshot.counts.entities} systems. {allCohorts.length} cohorts. One longitudinal map.</h1>
      <p class="lead" style="max-width:62ch">You cannot catch a flare without the baseline that came before it. So we record the frontier wide and early, every score frozen, with hash-pinned inputs and open raw provenance. Absence here means one thing: no baseline yet. The instrument is the coverage, and the coverage is what compounds.</p>

      <div class="stack" style="margin-top:2rem">
        {allCohorts.map(({ ind, sn }) => {
          const es = entitiesInCohort(sn.cohortKey);
          const withCite = es.filter((e) => e.axes.openalex_citation_momentum.status === 'present').length;
          return (
            <div class="panel" style="padding:20px 22px">
              <div class="row" style="justify-content:space-between;align-items:baseline">
                <h2 style="margin:0;font-size:1.12rem"><a href={`/industries/${ind.slug}/${sn.slug}/`} style="border:none">{sn.label}</a></h2>
                <span class="mono muted" style="font-size:.74rem">{ind.label} · {es.length} systems · {withCite} with citation axis</span>
              </div>
              <div class="row" style="margin-top:.9rem;gap:8px">
                {es.map((e) => (
                  <a href={`/e/${e.entity_id}/`} class="badge" style={`text-transform:none;${e.status==='rising'?'border-color:var(--velocity);color:var(--velocity-ink)':e.status==='watch'?'border-color:var(--citation);color:var(--citation-ink)':''}`}>{e.name}</a>
                ))}
              </div>
            </div>
          );
        })}
      </div>

      <div class="panel" style="padding:22px;margin-top:2rem;border-left:3px solid var(--citation)">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="color:var(--citation-ink)">Known gaps</div>
        <ul class="prose" style="margin-top:.7rem;margin-bottom:0">
          <li><strong>Closed-source systems.</strong> Private SaaS leaves few public, hard-to-game signals; this pilot tracks OSS / research-native systems where the data is rich and tamper-resistant.</li>
          <li><strong>Systems without a paper.</strong> Several tracked systems (e.g. in coding agents) have no academic publication, so they have no citation axis and cannot, by construction, satisfy the two-axis gate. They appear as single-axis.</li>
          <li><strong>New systems.</strong> Genuinely new (2024–25) systems lack the citation history to confirm momentum yet. Each weekly snapshot adds one data point. Confirmation arrives with time, not before it.</li>
          <li><strong>Beyond AI.</strong> The taxonomy reserves room beyond AI; this pilot measures three AI frontiers only.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p class="lead" style="max-width:62ch;margin-top:2rem">The record gets stronger the longer it runs. Only a continuous baseline can catch a flare against its own past, and ours starts here.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top:1.4rem"><a href={`/snapshots/${SNAP_DATE}/`}>See the full snapshot →</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
